As an HIV and AIDS educator, I can tell you that most people are unaware of the actual risks of contracting HIV. The risk of acquiring HIV from oral sex is close to zero. It's also important to know that even if exposed, there is a 72-hour window to take PEP (Post Exposure Prophylaxis), which makes HIV far less dangerous than many people believe. I understand that people may be worried about STIs, but it's crucial to educate, not stigmatize. In the US, the CDC provides a risk factor calculator that shows the risk of HIV from oral sex is equivalent to that of kissing and touching. People raised in my generation, the '80s and '90s, still hold onto a lot of misconceptions that have since been debunked. While it’s true that you can contract gonorrhea, chlamydia, and syphilis through oral sex, treating all STIs the same way only perpetuates stigma. Please work to reduce the stigma and help educate!

https://hivrisk.cdc.gov/risk-estimator-tool/

Personally I feel that any stunt or prank that involves gratification of potential life ending circumstances is an endorsement of both self harm for entertainment and making profit doing so. It's extremely disrespectful to anyone who has ever hanged or attempted to hang themselves, regardless of disclaimers or try not at home messaging. It does not ward people off from doing it, it presents these morbid situations as entertaining.

It's akin to that Paul disappointed that went into Aokigahara to find a body (which is illegal by the way), dance around it, laugh in shock to cope (understandably, seeing a lifeless body isn't something most people are accustomed to) recorded it, edited it, uploaded it and at no point he or any of his team questioned if it's wise to show it to any audience let alone the young impressionable minds of kids. And I haven't forgotten about the deluge of edgy teenagers egging youtubers on to explore that forest. Disgusting behaviour.

As for Kai himself, he responded apprehensive initially, then buckled under peer pressure. I fault his peers more for going through with it, they should've just called it off and tell the others there's a line people should not cross.

In re: KaiCenet

While I understand that shows get set up like this, especially for magic shows - thinking of all the wacky stuff that Cris Angel did, for example - this should not have aired. It should have been decided it would not be posted, shared, streamed. The second that anyone got uncomfortable, this should not have continued for filming purposes. This isn't all that unusual for stunt performances, and I think that sometimes gets lost in the controversy of it all. The performer also should also have had numerous disclosures and warnings ready for attendees, because performers can't just DO THIS legally without the right waivers and warnings. The blame here really is two-fold, regardless of KaiCenet was in on the concept or not, because he had guests that were uncomfortable and viewers who he should have reasonably known would be uncomfortable. If this were and AITA question, everyone here sucks.

When I was a boy, I remember one time watching a BBC nature documentary narrated by David Attenborough. There was one scene where a herd of elephants were drinking at an oasis, when suddenly a baby elephant slipped and fell into the mud. This young elephant came from another herd. It didn't have any familial ties with any of the elephants around, yet when the other elephants saw it sinking in the mud, it was a call to action as their only motivation was to prevent this little elephant from dying. A few of the adults came to its rescue, trying to pull it out of the mud with their trunks. But as it became evident that even a baby elephant weighed a lot, the entire herd got involved and before long they managed to save the young elephant. Attenborough remarked on how elephants understand the concept of death. Some even visit graveyards and interact with the bones of the deceased as it was shown in the documentary.

Honestly, as the video said, it's survival of the fittest. And notice how all the examples are from communal species where many individuals are living very close together. So there's an incentive to be nice and help others so you aren't ostracized and lose your access to mates.

Also, Rasp fish live in pairs and if one rasp is too parasitic and scaring away "customer fish", the other rasp will "break up" and find another rasp to co-op with.

Finally, altruistic is incentived when resources are abundant enough and competition is rare. Bonobos are some of the most altruistic apes. It stands to reason that they're environment has more food and almost no competition for that food. Conversely, chimpanzees live in a more food-scarce environment and need to compete with gorillas. So despite bonobos and chimps living across a river from each other, they evolved very different pack structures.

An essential feature of any capitalist system [from the USA to China] is that workers create more value than they receive in pay; they provide their labour [which could range from 8 - 10 hours a day] but are paid only for their "labour power", the value they create in, say, 4 hours. The surplus created is "surplus value", from which profits are derived.  In most capitalist societies workers have little or no control over the surplus - which is why wage differentials in some companies can be staggering, with higher management and CEOs taking pay and bonuses hundreds of times greater than the workers whose labour has created the surplus.

Here's an idea that I think sounds good in theory

Each week, a “base” amount of money is given to all members of society, including both people who have a job and people who don’t (the base amount is a set number and won’t change). People can earn more money each week by having a job. The amount of extra money that someone can receive from their job can be between two times and four times as much as the base amount, meaning that people that work can receive between three times and five times the amount of money in total as someone who doesn’t work. This applies to all jobs, including “organizer” jobs.

There are different job “groups” that are created to meet the needs of society at any given time. For example, there could be a security job group, a political job group, a transportation job group, etc. Each job group has individual job positions, as well as one organizer. Organizers control everything about the individual jobs in their group. This means that they can create new positions, they decide what qualifications are needed for each position, how long work hours would be for each position, etc. Anyone can choose a job position that they’re interested in, as long as they qualify for it, and anyone can quit their job at any given moment.

The most important position in this system is the “Director”. The Director is in control of other job groups, and has the ability to create new job groups, abolish old job groups, appoint new organizers into any job group, and fire organizers from any job group. The Director doesn’t have the ability to control any individual job positions inside of groups, but they can give advice to the organizers that they’ve appointed. Keep in mind, if the Director doesn’t like how an organizer is running a group, they can appoint someone else to take their place.

Each year, people will vote for whoever they want to become the Director. Whoever gets the most votes is able to become the Director, but if they decline, then the person with the next amount of votes can take the position. If two people get the same amount of votes and both want the position, then another vote will take place, and people will only be able to vote between the two. If people want to remove the current Director from their position, they can choose to vote “disapproval” against them. If one half of the population or higher chooses to “disapprove” of the Director, then that Director will be removed.

Only a single year-long term is allowed for the position of Director, unless they only served a partial term (in this case, serving a partial term does not include getting removed due to disapproval votes). This means that nobody can be voted into the Director position more than two times. But Organizers currently appointed can stay in their position indefinitely, until they either get kicked out by the Director or if they choose to step down.

People will spend the money that they receive on goods, and the money that they spent will then be redistributed. If there is not enough money to redistribute, money can be printed, and the areas where money is printed will need to be monitored to prevent stealing, although this won’t be needed if money is transferred digitally or through credit cards.

Prices of goods can increase or decrease, depending on how much is produced and what the population size is. If there are too few people doing a certain job, the income for the job can be increased, and the income for jobs that are less needed can be decreased. This means that when goods become more expensive, people will want better paying jobs (which will be the more needed jobs), meaning that goods will be produced more efficiently, which decreases their cost.

Artist here. I have been waiting for Apple to add hover and barrel roll rotation since the very first iPad. The only other stylus that could do it was the Wacom Art Pen, which they discontinued earlier this year. It makes a huge difference for artists used to traditional media, so honestly those things on their own are worth the upgrade.

I am disappointed that there is still no eraser though. I know they added features to swap tools, but it’s not the same. The eraser is fast and intuitive and eventually they need to break down and add it. I’d prefer that over haptics any day. Wacom is still superior in that way, plus no charging necessary so they can create a comfortable grip, unlike Apple Pencil with its flat edge that is so uncomfortable to hold long term. Apple still needs to make better tips that are narrower, but they are steadily narrowing the gap which is nice to see.

One thing I’d be curious about for the matte screen texture is durability because that texture is much better to draw on. Wacom uses textured screens specifically to make drawing feel more intuitive. I have to add a PaperFeel screen protector to my iPad to get a similar experience, so I’m wondering if this is another feature that was intended for artists but marketed to the masses as being anti-glare to justify the cost of development. If it can hold up against scratches well, then I would go matte every time right from the start to avoid bubbles in screen protectors. That would explain why it’s only on the higher end models since they know their artist audience will want it.

Procreate for painting and Nomad for 3D modeling are still some of the best software on the iPad and in many cases can outperform full computer software, so they really needed their hardware to catch up. From my perspective, this feels like a long time in the making. It certainly isn’t going to appeal to everyone, but it’s not supposed to.

I don’t care about thinness though. Honestly it’s awkward to hold and draw on because you feel like it’s going to bend on you. A lot of times I just wanna kick back and draw with it on my lap or stomach, but I feel like I need a lap stand to use it that way which defeats the whole thinness aspect. Better battery life would be preferred.

As far as where to put the pencil for charging, I think they were attempting to make it feel natural for both right and left-handed users. Putting it in the middle makes it easy to reach regardless of handedness. It’s better than when companies just default to right-handed interfaces. So much of my life has been a struggle because most of the world is engineered for the opposite of what I need. Like it would be nice if Apple let us calibrate touch for lefties. It defaults to what looks right to right-handed users, so I often hit the wrong letters when typing because it’s offset in the opposite direction from what I need. Similar issues pop up with software menus and interfaces. Wow, this was one of the most interesting episodes I've seen. That first job though 🤣 caught me off guard. I knew about a few of these jobs, one of them in particular because I used to work at a grocery store. The cutting room was located amongst the areas where you'd access the coolers in the back. I couldn't really tell from clip, but I would assume the person cutting the fruit would be wearing a cutting glove. It's basically a chainmail glove you wear underneath your working gloves, that's what we had at the store I used to work at. We didn't have fruit cutting as a like all day position, in fact most of the positions at the grocery store were interchangeable by everyone. Everyone hired starts at the beginning position, referred to as a courtesy clerk, and from there you move up. This way, in case the store happens to become extremely busy or chaotic (especially helpful during times of crisis) anyone can fill in for any position if need be. Back in late 2018 or early 2019, during my senior year of high school, I had an experience I’ll never forget. I have voice recordings from that night, capturing what my friend and I saw.

We were out on a trail that led to a bench overlooking the small town where we lived. We had gone there to enjoy the sunset and the night sky.

Just to clarify, I wasn’t on any drugs, so I know some of you might be skeptical.

As the sun was setting behind us, we were looking out over the town when my friend noticed something unusual over the mountain range in the distance. It was a glowing object, moving down the mountain at a speed much faster than the local passenger planes that typically fly from the nearby county airport. We kept watching, captivated by this strange phenomenon. The mountain was large, and the object was covering a significant distance much more quickly than anything we’d seen before. The sunset sky was a vibrant mix of orange and red, which made the object even more striking.

Then, without warning, the object suddenly accelerated and disappeared. It was gone in the blink of an eye. My friend immediately jumped up and ran half a mile back to the car. I tried to tell him to stop, but he wouldn’t listen. I was honestly shocked by his reaction—especially since he’s an avid hunter who hikes and camps late at night without fear. He’s not religious, so there was no influence from any sort of supernatural or demonic beliefs. His fear seemed genuine, and that left me wondering what we had just witnessed.
